				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The point that I was trying to make is that while some laws seem to make sense on paper, in practice it may be another story. <br /><br />Prohibition may have seemed like a good idea in theory, but when testing in a real life social economy, it falls flat on its face. I think the same can be said about old roms for video games. Companies may try and take down rom sites and say that it is illegal, yet the reality is that everyone and their grandma is going to do it. So why not change the laws to better our society?<br /><br />Here is something to note about copyrights.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">a Congressional Research Service study indicated that “only 2 percent of works between 55 and 75 years old continue to retain commercial value. For the other 98 percent of works, no one is benefiting from the continued copyright during the last part of the term.</div> <br /><br />Source<br /><br /> <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/xw4gwd/public-domain-drought">https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/arti ... in-drought</a><!-- m --></div>

